11 287.243. 1. This section shall be known and may be cited as the "Line of Duty
12 Compensation Act".
13 2. As used in this section, unless otherwise provided, the following words shall mean:
14 (1) "Air ambulance pilot", a person certified as an air ambulance pilot in accordance
15 with sections 190.001 to 190.245 and corresponding regulations applicable to air ambulances
16 adopted by the department of health and senior services;
17 (2) "Air ambulance registered professional nurse", a person licensed as a registered
18 professional nurse in accordance with sections 335.011 to 335.096 and corresponding regulations
19 adopted by the state board of nursing, 20 CSR 2200-4, et seq., who provides registered
20 professional nursing services as a flight nurse in conjunction with an air ambulance program that
21 is certified in accordance with sections 190.001 to 190.245 and the corresponding regulations
22 applicable to such programs;
23 (3) "Air ambulance registered respiratory therapist", a person licensed as a registered
24 respiratory therapist in accordance with sections 334.800 to 334.930 and corresponding
25 regulations adopted by the state board for respiratory care, who provides respiratory therapy
26 services in conjunction with an air ambulance program that is certified in accordance with
27 sections 190.001 to 190.245 and corresponding regulations applicable to such programs;
28 (4) "Child", any natural, illegitimate, adopted, or posthumous child or stepchild of a
29 deceased public safety officer who, at the time of the public safety officer's fatality is:
30 (a) Eighteen years of age or under;
31 (b) Over eighteen years of age and a student, as defined in 5 U.S.C. Section 8101; or
32 (c) Over eighteen years of age and incapable of self-support because of physical or
33 mental disability;
34 (5) "Emergency medical technician", a person licensed in emergency medical care in
35 accordance with standards prescribed by sections 190.001 to 190.245 and by rules adopted by
36 the department of health and senior services under sections 190.001 to 190.245;
37 (6) "Firefighter", any person, including a volunteer firefighter, employed by the state or a
38 local governmental entity as an employer defined under subsection 1 of section 287.030, or
Page 5 of 41

6771H02.37H
1 otherwise serving as a member or officer of a fire department either for the purpose of the
2 prevention or control of fire or the underwater recovery of drowning victims;
3 (7) "Flight crew member", an individual engaged in flight responsibilities with an air
4 ambulance licensed in accordance with sections 190.001 to 190.245 and corresponding
5 regulations applicable to such programs;
6 (8) "Killed in the line of duty", when any person defined in this section loses his or her
7 life when:
8 (a) Death is caused by an accident, illness, or the willful act of violence of another;
9 (b) The public safety officer is in the active performance of his or her duties in his or her
10 respective profession and there is a relationship between the accident, illness, or commission of
11 the act of violence and the performance of the duty, even if the individual is off duty; the public
12 safety officer is traveling to or from employment; or the public safety officer is taking any meal
13 break or other break which takes place while that individual is on duty;
14 (c) Death is the natural and probable consequence of the injury or illness; and
15 (d) Death occurs within three hundred weeks from the date the injury was received or
16 illness was contracted.
17
18 The term excludes death resulting from the willful misconduct or intoxication of the public
19 safety officer. The division of workers' compensation shall have the burden of proving such
20 willful misconduct or intoxication;
21 (9) "Law enforcement officer", any person employed by the state or a local
22 governmental entity as a police officer, peace officer certified under chapter 590, or serving as an
23 auxiliary police officer or in some like position involving the enforcement of the law and
24 protection of the public interest at the risk of that person's life;
25 (10) "Local governmental entity", includes counties, municipalities, townships, board or
26 other political subdivision, cities under special charter, or under the commission form of
27 government, fire protection districts, ambulance districts, and municipal corporations;
28 (11) "Public safety officer", any law enforcement officer, firefighter, uniformed
29 employee of the office of the state fire marshal, emergency medical technician, police officer,
30 capitol police officer, parole officer, probation officer, state correctional employee, water safety
31 officer, park ranger, conservation officer, or highway patrolman employed by the state of
32 Missouri or a political subdivision thereof who is killed in the line of duty or any emergency
33 medical technician, air ambulance pilot, air ambulance registered professional nurse, air
34 ambulance registered respiratory therapist, or flight crew member who is killed in the line of
35 duty;
36 (12) "State", the state of Missouri and its departments, divisions, boards, bureaus,
37 commissions, authorities, and colleges and universities;
Page 6 of 41

6771H02.37H
1 (13) "Volunteer firefighter", a person having principal employment other than as a
2 firefighter, but who is carried on the rolls of a regularly constituted fire department either for the
3 purpose of the prevention or control of fire or the underwater recovery of drowning victims, the
4 members of which are under the jurisdiction of the corporate authorities of a city, village,
5 incorporated town, or fire protection district. Volunteer firefighter shall not mean an individual
6 who volunteers assistance without being regularly enrolled as a firefighter.
7 3. (1) A claim for compensation under this section shall be filed by survivors of the
8 deceased with the division of workers' compensation not later than two years from the date of
9 death of a public safety officer. If a claim is made within two years of the date of death of a
10 public safety officer killed in the line of duty, compensation shall be paid, if the division finds
11 that the claimant is entitled to compensation under this section.
12 (2) The amount of compensation paid to the claimant shall be one hundred thousand
13 dollars, subject to appropriation, for death occurring on or after June 19, 2009.
14 4. Any compensation awarded under the provisions of this section shall be distributed as
15 follows:
16 (1) To the surviving spouse of the public safety officer if there is no child who survived
17 the public safety officer;
18 (2) Fifty percent to the surviving child, or children, in equal shares, and fifty percent to
19 the surviving spouse if there is at least one child who survived the public safety officer, and a
20 surviving spouse of the public safety officer;
21 (3) To the surviving child, or children, in equal shares, if there is no surviving spouse of
22 the public safety officer;
23 (4) If there is no surviving spouse of the public safety officer and no surviving child:
24 (a) To the surviving individual, or individuals, in shares per the designation or,
25 otherwise, in equal shares, designated by the public safety officer to receive benefits under this
26 subsection in the most recently executed designation of beneficiary of the public safety officer
27 on file at the time of death with the public safety agency, organization, or unit; or
28 (b) To the surviving individual, or individuals, in equal shares, designated by the public
29 safety officer to receive benefits under the most recently executed life insurance policy of the
30 public safety officer on file at the time of death with the public safety agency, organization, or
31 unit if there is no individual qualifying under paragraph (a) of this subdivision;
32 (5) To the surviving parent, or parents, in equal shares, of the public safety officer if
33 there is no individual qualifying under subdivision (1), (2), (3), or (4) of this subsection; or
34 (6) To the surviving individual, or individuals, in equal shares, who would qualify under
35 the definition of the term "child" but for age if there is no individual qualifying under
36 subdivision (1), (2), (3), (4), or (5) of this subsection.
37 5. Notwithstanding subsection 3 of this section, no compensation is payable under this
38 section unless a claim is filed within the time specified under this section setting forth:
Page 7 of 41

6771H02.37H
1 (1) The name, address, and title or designation of the position in which the public safety
2 officer was serving at the time of his or her death;
3 (2) The name and address of the claimant;
4 (3) A full, factual account of the circumstances resulting in or the course of events
5 causing the death at issue; and
6 (4) Such other information that is reasonably required by the division.
7
8 When a claim is filed, the division of workers' compensation shall make an investigation for
9 substantiation of matters set forth in the application.
10 6. The compensation provided for under this section is in addition to, and not exclusive
11 of, any pension rights, death benefits, or other compensation the claimant may otherwise be
12 entitled to by law.
13 7. Neither employers nor workers' compensation insurers shall have subrogation rights
14 against any compensation awarded for claims under this section. Such compensation shall not
15 be assignable, shall be exempt from attachment, garnishment, and execution, and shall not be
16 subject to setoff or counterclaim, or be in any way liable for any debt, except that the division or
17 commission may allow as lien on the compensation, reasonable attorney's fees for services in
18 connection with the proceedings for compensation if the services are found to be necessary.
19 Such fees are subject to regulation as set forth in section 287.260.
20 8. Any person seeking compensation under this section who is aggrieved by the decision
21 of the division of workers' compensation regarding his or her compensation claim, may make
22 application for a hearing as provided in section 287.450. The procedures applicable to the
23 processing of such hearings and determinations shall be those established by this chapter.
24 Decisions of the administrative law judge under this section shall be binding, subject to review
25 by either party under the provisions of section 287.480.
26 9. [Pursuant to section 23.253 of the Missouri sunset act:
27 (1) The provisions of the new program authorized under this section shall automatically
28 sunset on December 31, 2031, unless reauthorized by an act of the general assembly; and
29 (2) If such program is reauthorized, the program authorized under this section shall
30 automatically sunset twelve years after the effective date of the reauthorization of this section;
31 and
32 (3) This section shall terminate on September first of the calendar year immediately
33 following the calendar year in which the program authorized under this section is sunset.] This
34 section shall not be subject to the provisions of the Missouri sunset act under sections 23.250 to
35 23.298.
36 10. The provisions of this section, unless specified, shall not be subject to other
37 provisions of this chapter.
Page 8 of 41

6771H02.37H
1 11. There is hereby created in the state treasury the "Line of Duty Compensation Fund",
2 which shall consist of moneys appropriated to the fund and any voluntary contributions, gifts, or
3 bequests to the fund. The state treasurer shall be custodian of the fund and shall approve
4 disbursements from the fund in accordance with sections 30.170 and 30.180. Upon
5 appropriation, money in the fund shall be used solely for paying claims under this section.
6 Notwithstanding the provisions of section 33.080 to the contrary, any moneys remaining in the
7 fund at the end of the biennium shall not revert to the credit of the general revenue fund. The
8 state treasurer shall invest moneys in the fund in the same manner as other funds are invested.
9 Any interest and moneys earned on such investments shall be credited to the fund.
10 12. The division shall promulgate rules to administer this section, including but not
11 limited to the appointment of claims to multiple claimants, record retention, and procedures for
12 information requests. Any rule or portion of a rule, as that term is defined in section 536.010,
