3 the department of corrections pursuant to an interagency agreement shall be housed and
4 managed separately from offenders in the custody of the department of corrections, and except
5 for occasional instances of supervised incidental contact, shall be segregated from such
6 offenders. If the department of mental health and the department of corrections have entered
7 into an interagency agreement as provided in this subsection, the department of corrections is
8 authorized to enter into one or more contract agreements as may be necessary to perform the
9 agreed upon responsibilities of the department of corrections under the interagency agreement
10 including, but not limited to, a contract agreement with one or more licensed professionals or
11 providers of health care services to provide health care services to the persons identified in this
12 subsection.
13 5. The department of mental health is authorized to enter into a contract agreement with
14 one or more county jails in Missouri for the confinement of persons ordered to the department of
15 mental health after a determination by the court that such persons may meet the definition of a
16 sexually violent predator or for the confinement of persons ordered to the department of mental
17 health after a finding of probable cause under section 632.489. Such persons who are in the
18 confinement of a county jail pursuant to a contract agreement shall be housed and managed
19 separately from offenders in the custody of the county jail, and except for occasional instances of
20 supervised incidental contact, shall be segregated from such offenders.
21 6. The department of mental health is authorized to enter into an interagency agreement
22 with the department of corrections for the control and care, including health care services, of
23 persons committed to the department of mental health by the court as a sexually violent predator,
24 provided the department of corrections has necessary space and services available and the
25 director of the department of corrections has agreed to provide such control and care through an
26 interagency agreement with the department of mental health. Such persons who are in the
27 control and care of the department of corrections under an interagency agreement shall be
28 housed and managed separately from offenders in the custody of the department of corrections,
29 and except for occasional instances of supervised incidental contact, shall be segregated from
30 such offenders. If the department of mental health and the department of corrections have
31 entered into an interagency agreement as provided in this subsection, the department of
Page 39 of 41

6771H02.37H
1 corrections is authorized to enter into one or more contract agreements as may be necessary to
2 perform the agreed upon responsibilities of the department of corrections under the interagency
3 agreement including, but not limited to, a contract agreement with one or more licensed
4 professionals or providers of health care services to provide health care services to the persons
5 identified in this subsection.
6 7. The department of mental health is authorized to enter into a contract agreement with
7 one or more licensed professionals or providers of health care or mental health care services to
8 provide health care or mental health care services to persons ordered to the department of mental
9 health after a determination by the court that such persons may meet the definition of a sexually
10 violent predator, persons ordered to the department of mental health after a finding of probable
11 cause under section 632.489, and persons committed for control, care, and treatment by the
12 department of mental health under sections 632.480 to 632.513.
13 8. If the court or jury is not satisfied by clear and convincing evidence that the person is
14 a sexually violent predator, the court shall direct the person's release.
15 [7.] 9. Upon a mistrial, the court shall direct that the person be held at an appropriate
16 secure facility, including, but not limited to, a county jail, until another trial is conducted. If the
17 person is ordered to the department of mental health, the director of the department of mental
18 health shall determine the appropriate secure facility to house the person. Any subsequent trial
19 following a mistrial shall be held within ninety days of the previous trial, unless such subsequent
20 trial is continued as provided in section 632.492.
21 632.504. Nothing in sections 632.480 to 632.513 shall prohibit a person from filing a
22 petition for release pursuant to sections 632.480 to 632.513. However, if a person has previously
23 filed a petition for release without the [director's] director of the department of mental health's
24 approval and the court determined either upon review of the petition or following a hearing that
25 the petitioner's petition was frivolous or that the petitioner's condition had not so changed that
26 the person was safe to be at large, then the court shall deny the subsequent petition unless the
27 petition contains facts upon which a court could find the condition of the petitioner had so
28 changed that a hearing was warranted. Upon receipt of a first or subsequent petition from
29 committed persons without the director's approval, the court shall endeavor whenever possible to
30 review the petition and determine if the petition is based upon frivolous grounds and if so shall
31 deny the petition without a hearing.
Page 40 of 41

6771H02.37H
1 632.520. 1. For purposes of this section, the following terms mean:
2 (1) "Employee of the department of mental health", a person who is an employee of the
3 department of mental health, an employee or contracted employee of a subcontractor of the
4 department of mental health, or an employee or contracted employee of a subcontractor of an
5 entity [responsible for confining offenders] under an interagency agreement or contract with the
6 department of mental health as authorized by section 632.495;
7 (2) "Offender", a person ordered to the department of mental health after a determination
8 by the court that the person meets the definition of a sexually violent predator, a person ordered
9 to the department of mental health after a finding of probable cause under section 632.489, or a
10 person committed for control, care, and treatment by the department of mental health under
11 sections 632.480 to 632.513;
12 (3) "Secure facility", a facility operated by the department of mental health or an entity
13 [responsible for confining offenders] designated by the department of mental health to confine
14 offenders or provide control and care to offenders as authorized by section 632.495.
15 2. No offender shall knowingly commit violence to an employee of the department of
16 mental health or to another offender housed in a secure facility. Violation of this subsection shall
17 be a class B felony.
18 3. No offender shall knowingly damage any building or other property owned or
19 operated by the department of mental health. Violation of this subsection shall be a class D
20 felony."; and
21
22 Further amend said bill by amending the title, enacting clause, and intersectional references
23 accordingly.
